text.tspan: RIPARIAN ENHANCEMENT PROJECT
Lake Maraetai
Waikato River Trails
Bye-bye Blacberry and welcome Wineberry
Blackberry and other weeds are being eliminated
from this area and replaced by the likes of Wineberry
and other native plant species. Kowhai, hebe, carex,
pittosporum, cordyline and Griselinia are just some
of them.
The native planting is thanks to a major
environmental enhancement project which will
see tens of thousands of plants and trees taking
up residency along sectors of the Waikato River's
riparian areas. These areas are all accessible to the
public via the Waikato River Trails.
Removal of weeds through this area is a long-term
plan. Up until late 2011 most of the area between
the farm fencing and the Waikato River was infected
with weeds
of them.
In some parts of this area the soil structure includes
pumices and planting will assist with erosion control.
The planting will not-only increase the beauty of the
riverside and play a role in controlling erosion and
weeds, it will also improve water quality and act as a
nutrient trap and food source for birds.
Waikato River Authority is principle funder of this
project, with assistance from the Waikato Catchment
Ecological Enhancement Trust, South Waikato
Environmental Initiatives Fund, Waikato Regional
Council and Wairarapa Moana Inc. It is also backed
by strong support from local community volunteers.
The project is a collaborative effort between these
parties and the Waikato River Trails Trust, with
support from major sponsor Mighty River Power.
All parties are immensly proud of being involved in
this project with its focus on enhancing the natural
beauty of the Waikato River and its surrounds, for the
enjoyment of the public.
